{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640954"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:20:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17850"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17850"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116684"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10564"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17850"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98671"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1992"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10057"},{"type":"tags","id":"10061"},{"type":"tags","id":"10063"},{"type":"tags","id":"13209"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24633"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring sustained aerobic exercise, skeletal muscle cells metabolise glucose through several different pathways to meet energy demands.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the predominant metabolic fate of glucose in exercising skeletal muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anaerobic metabolism to lactate and ATP","Complete oxidation to carbon dioxide and ATP","Storage conversion to glycogen reserves","Transamination to form amino acids","Lipogenic conversion to fatty acids"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring aerobic exercise, skeletal muscle primarily utilises glucose through \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete oxidation to carbon dioxide and ATP\u003C/strong\u003E. This process consists of glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation, which together yield approximately 38 ATP molecules per glucose molecule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaerobic metabolism to lactate and ATP\u003C/strong\u003E occurs primarily during intense exercise when oxygen is limited, yielding only two ATP molecules per glucose. \u003Cstrong\u003EStorage conversion to glycogen reserves\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during rest and recovery, not during active exercise when energy demands are high. \u003Cstrong\u003ETransamination to form amino acids\u003C/strong\u003E is not a significant pathway in skeletal muscle, as amino acids are typically derived from protein breakdown. \u003Cstrong\u003ELipogenic conversion to fatty acids\u003C/strong\u003E occurs predominantly in the liver and adipose tissue, not in skeletal muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe complete oxidation pathway maximises energy yield from glucose, making it the most efficient and predominant pathway during sustained aerobic exercise.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In skeletal muscle, glucose is primarily used for ATP production through complete oxidation.","Complete oxidation of glucose involves glycolysis, the citric acid cycle, and oxidative phosphorylation.","Glycolysis alone, leading to lactate production, is less efficient in terms of ATP yield compared to complete oxidation."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Carbohydrate Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Jan 4;13(1):a040568. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040568.","Hall JE. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2021. Chapter 85; pg. 1076."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98671"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17850"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98671","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98671"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:12:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms"